# rename the columns with slashes
global_cases <- global_cases %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`) 

global_deaths <- global_deaths %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`) 

global_recoveries <- global_recoveries %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`)

I am getting my data from the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University. They have a GitHub repository for global cases, deaths, and recoveries, so I will be using this repository.

The three files here contain a lot of information, but they show a tally of cases or deaths or recoveries per country per day, with each day being a new column. We have a very wide table. Since I want to more easily see the number of cases, deaths and recoveries, I will have to transform the data.

Also, since these datasets create wide tables, excuse me as I show the summary of only one of them. Showing the summaries of the other two would take up a lot of space. The other two datasets have a similar structure, with deaths and recoveries taking the place of cases in their respective datasets.

However, for recoveries, it appears that we don’t have recorded data past August 4, 2021, as we get 0s from August 5, 2021 onward. I will also have to address this in my transformation.

recoveries_last_available_date <- "2021-08-04"
# get philippine cases
ph_cases <- global_cases %>% 
  filter(Country_Region == "Philippines") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols= -c(Province_State,
                        Country_Region,
                        Lat,
                        Long),
               names_to="date",
               values_to="cases") %>%
  select(-c(Lat, Long))

I’m also more interested in seeing things after the Philippines started having cases, so I only retained the rows that had at least one case.

I would like to create a model to see how things would play out in the future. I think it’s more accurate to use only this year’s data with regards to case fatality rate since the outbreak was such a sudden shock to the world last year. I think now that the world has had a chance to stabilize somewhat, this year’s numbers should be more relevant.

Conclusion

It appears that there is a downward trend in the case fatality rates for both countries. The rates for both countries appear to continue going down, as predicted by my models.

It appears that Japan has a slightly lower case fatality rate as of September 2021. Perhaps it was a good thing for me to have come here, after all. I do miss seeing my family, however.

I could only look forward to the day that the numbers say zero. However, this may be impossible, and I have to temper my expectations so.

I have heard that age is a comorbidity when it came to COVID. Given that Japan’s population is aging, I would have expected that Japan’s case fatality rate would have been higher. However, I should also take into consideration that Japan’s healthcare system could be superior compared to the Philippines’s.

Focusing solely on raw cases, deaths, and recoveries might not paint an accurate picture, so I opted to go for a metric like the case fatality rate. This would control for the different numbers of cases and deaths.
